    "narrative": "The Ghost Ride the WHIP lineup is anchored by two high-upside plays today: **James Wood** (75.94) and **Mickey Moniak** (75.75). **James Wood** benefits from the prime leadoff spot against McGreevy, capitalizing on a 14% boost from a favorable park and soft pitching. Meanwhile, **Mickey Moniak** is in an ideal smash spot against Javier; the combination of a 14% park factor, a 14% platoon edge, and a high-leverage #3 batting slot makes him a mandatory start. **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (75.73) rounds out our elite tier, as he gets a massive 15% skill boost against a favorable Severino matchup. Even with the slight negative offset from the opposing catcher\u2019s pop time, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** remains a primary target for stolen base production, which remains our highest priority category.\n\nWe are navigating a few tactical risks today, most notably with **Zach McKinstry** (52.83). While his score is bolstered by a 12% SP skill advantage and a wind-aided projection, his status remains \"Lineup Pending,\" requiring us to remain vigilant regarding his confirmed position. We are also proceeding with caution regarding **Vinnie Pasquantino** (48.67), whose efficiency is suppressed by a significant 15% platoon penalty against the left-handed Cantillo, keeping him just above our \"Marginal\" threshold. **Austin Riley** (44.64) stands as the most notable bench decision; he provided the highest floor among our reserves, but he was ultimately relegated to the bench because his 19% SP skill penalty against Detmers rendered him less efficient than our active roster, which is currently optimized to maximize platoon and park advantages. **Trevor Story** (67.62) serves as our wildcard; despite a \"Wind In\" warning negating some of the park benefit, the matchup against Drohan\u2019s 10.13 xERA provides the highest individual run-scoring potential of the slate.",
